00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:16.519
I'm really curious.

00:05:16.519 --> 00:05:17.519
When did you, how did you get involved with computer programming?

00:05:17.519 --> 00:05:18.519
Yeah.

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:21.760
Well, so, so creating text adventures, that was kind of the first thing.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:29.040
And then also when I went to, I went to Rice University in Houston.

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:36.920
And there was a class called CAM 210, which a friend was taking, taught by kind of this

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:41.399
majestic bearded human named Steve Cox.

00:05:41.399 --> 00:05:46.600
I'm not sure if you encountered him Hadley, but he was like wonderful, wonderful human.

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:50.440
Usually taught CAM 210 using MATLAB.

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:53.559
But for whatever reason, like this semester was teaching it using Python.

00:05:53.559 --> 00:05:59.160
Like Python plus a lot of the numeric and scientific computing packages that were kind

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:01.480
of earlier days at the time.

00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:06.079
And I remember like hanging out with my friend who was going through a lot of the, a lot

00:06:06.079 --> 00:06:11.119
of the tutorials and like trying to bang their head against the wall to start using Python

00:06:11.119 --> 00:06:15.040
and got really enchanted by this idea that people would build things and then like release

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:17.359
them out into the world for zero dollars.

00:06:17.359 --> 00:06:18.359
Oh, cool.

00:06:18.359 --> 00:06:19.359
Yeah.

00:06:19.359 --> 00:06:25.640
So I was, I would say like started programming, just text adventures, making mods to like

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:27.600
Grand Theft Auto.

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.799
Not really like thinking anything of it when I was younger.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:35.399
And then I got to school and like Python was kind of the first thing that, that helped

00:06:35.399 --> 00:06:36.760
me understand open source.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:37.760
Yeah.

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:38.760
Cool.

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:41.079
And were you, would you say you're doing a lot of sort of data science work out of school

00:06:41.079 --> 00:06:42.720
or what kind of?

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:46.079
So, so it's really, it's really fascinating.

00:06:46.079 --> 00:06:51.160
I feel like there was this period of time where a lot of people were doing data sciency

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:54.760
style things, but the word did, like the term did not exist.

00:06:54.760 --> 00:07:03.040
So, so for open source, my background, I was doing kind of geophysics, specifically planetary

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:04.279
sciences research.

00:07:04.279 --> 00:07:09.640
So I interned at the Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics and Southwest Research Institute

00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:15.160
in San Antonio and was doing a lot of work to understand lunar ultraviolet.

00:07:15.239 --> 00:07:19.399
So there were these spacecraft that had a whole bunch of data that would get pulled

00:07:19.399 --> 00:07:25.720
down to help understand lunar albedo or some of the other, some of the other things like

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:29.480
metrics that the spacecraft were capturing.

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:34.200
And the expectation was that you would analyze them using something called IDL, which was

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:39.920
more painful than MATLAB and, but I had, I had like Python existed.

00:07:39.920 --> 00:07:42.079
And so that was, that was a little bit easier.

00:07:42.079 --> 00:07:47.880
And so, so I ended up, if I needed to visualize data or kind of understand it, instead of

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:52.279
like trying to bang my head against the wall and understand IDL, apologies to anybody who

00:07:52.279 --> 00:07:58.160
might've been working on IDL, I just used Python and started working on it like that.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:02.760
And we, yeah, and we were also really fortunate in Texas in the sense that like just down

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:06.600
the way in Austin, there were a whole bunch of people that were also like nerds into open

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:10.000
source libraries for scientific computing.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:16.839
So like the Unthought Canopy dudes and you know, the Anaconda team now, though they had

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:22.320
previously had another name, I think Continuum Analytics or something similar.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:26.399
So, so I feel like I really lucked into it, honestly.

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:30.959
It's kind of hard to imagine now, but at the time it was such a crazy idea to like, that

00:08:30.959 --> 00:08:37.880
you might use like free software to do serious work instead of paying like money for it.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:41.000
Like now it just seems like it is kind of like weird, right?

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.880
We're just using all this free stuff that people make from out of the goodness of their

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:46.440
hearts and give to the world.

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:47.440
100%.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:51.520
Especially in the oil and gas, like in the geophysics, oil and gas industry world.

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:54.239
Because so much of that software is proprietary.

00:08:54.239 --> 00:09:02.599
Like even today, like there, there's something called Petrel, the one of the software applications

00:09:02.599 --> 00:09:04.880
for understanding subsurface data.

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:08.799
And I think it's like $100,000 a seat per year or something.

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:12.000
So like, like crazy, crazy amounts.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.679
But most of the things that you do on Petrel, if not all, you could easily do with just

00:09:15.679 --> 00:09:17.479
like Python and open source libraries.

00:09:18.528 --> 00:09:25.008
Yeah, so it does feel like a really — it feels so strange to even think about it right now,

00:09:25.008 --> 00:09:30.528
of how different everything was back then. It was also the situation where

00:09:31.328 --> 00:09:35.408
I remember going to my professors and being like, hey, I really like programming. I think

00:09:35.408 --> 00:09:40.048
this is really cool. We should totally have libraries for doing earth sciences-related

00:09:40.048 --> 00:09:44.848
things. And my professors being like, no, that's not real science. Why are you wasting your time?

00:09:45.408 --> 00:09:51.167
Nobody needs — if you're writing libraries, that's not actually contributing to your career.

00:09:51.167 --> 00:09:52.527
It's actually a waste of time.

00:09:52.527 --> 00:09:56.367
Yeah, but tooling versus doing the actual research.

00:09:57.487 --> 00:10:04.288
And now it's — if you're not writing code or using code to analyze data,

00:10:04.288 --> 00:10:05.408
you're probably not doing research.

00:10:05.408 --> 00:10:06.207
What are you doing?

00:10:07.408 --> 00:10:11.728
I'm really curious. You were somebody who has been in the AI space before it was cool,

00:10:11.728 --> 00:10:16.527
and I'm putting that in air quotes. How did you make that jump from, you know, I'm doing

00:10:18.207 --> 00:10:23.328
geo stuff to now I'm doing AI, I'm doing deep learning, working on things like tensorflow?

00:10:23.328 --> 00:10:30.767
Yeah, so geophysics — geophysics is like — I always feel like we are the

00:10:32.608 --> 00:10:39.568
sort of the more stay-at-home type kind of earth scientists, right? We're the ones that

00:10:39.568 --> 00:10:44.928
care about computers and that are trying to find more efficient ways to analyze data.

00:10:45.648 --> 00:10:52.928
And the geophysics world actually adopted GPUs before most everybody else, for things like

00:10:52.928 --> 00:10:58.688
velocity modeling, like fluid dynamics simulations, like all sorts of stuff, even before the gaming

00:10:58.688 --> 00:11:08.288
industry kind of like caught on to GPUs. And so I was doing that a lot for some of the geophysics

00:11:08.288 --> 00:11:13.648
work, just like trying to bang my head against CUDA. And when tensorflow was first released,

00:11:13.648 --> 00:11:22.048
I don't think most people remember, but it was CPU only. So you were doing analysis across

00:11:22.048 --> 00:11:29.888
large numbers of CPUs, not really thinking about GPUs until later on. And so that was something

00:11:29.888 --> 00:11:35.327
that I could do that was helpful of just kind of like, hey, you're thinking about accelerators now.

00:11:35.327 --> 00:11:44.368
I know CUDA. I can help with that. And it's a useful way to kind of collaborate with the team,

00:11:44.368 --> 00:11:49.487
I think. If somebody releases an open source library and you contribute to it or you build

00:11:49.487 --> 00:11:53.728
something with it and talk about it, then they get a flavor of what it would be like to work

00:11:53.728 --> 00:11:59.808
with you as a person. There's such a strong pipeline of people from like physical sciences

00:11:59.808 --> 00:12:05.247
like that too. It feels like AI. There's the whole conference about ex-astronomers, now data

00:12:05.247 --> 00:12:10.928
scientists. It's so surprising to see how all this comes together. Yeah, linear algebra. And

00:12:10.928 --> 00:12:19.648
like also, you know, JAX has the same spec as NumPy. And a lot of the libraries have the

00:12:19.648 --> 00:12:27.327
same like general flavor of scientific computing libraries. So like SciPy for scientific computing

00:12:27.327 --> 00:12:36.368
processes. So I think there's definitely a lot of love between the kind of physics and

00:12:36.368 --> 00:12:43.808
mathematics world and the JAX world. Also, like all of the JAX machine learning frameworks authors

00:12:43.808 --> 00:12:51.008
came from mostly like mathematics backgrounds, which is quite cool. Yeah, it's interesting. It

00:12:51.008 --> 00:12:57.808
seems like you've done a lot of both like development and product management and DevRel

00:12:57.808 --> 00:13:03.648
engineering. Yep. When did you know this was kind of the work that you really wanted to be doing?

00:13:03.648 --> 00:13:11.568
How did this work come together? Yeah, I think I, again, just like I feel so stupidly lucky,

00:13:11.568 --> 00:13:17.487
like in the sense that I've just always done whatever I thought would be useful and interesting.

00:13:18.047 --> 00:13:24.528
And now we're in this really happy place where a long time ago, people would kind of artificially

00:13:24.528 --> 00:13:28.687
put people into buckets of like, oh, you're an engineer, you're a product human, you're,

00:13:29.648 --> 00:13:34.208
you know, a design human, you're like these other things. And you could only wear this one hat,

00:13:34.208 --> 00:13:39.328
which is really frustrating if you like doing a whole bunch of stuff. And now we're in this place

00:13:39.328 --> 00:13:46.847
where it's just like, oh, you want to do data visualization and you want to do like you want

00:13:46.847 --> 00:13:52.448
to understand large scale datasets and you also want to be able to build tools in order to do all

00:13:52.448 --> 00:13:58.527
of the above, like go for it. Like that's you can you can be this auteur of anything you want to

00:13:58.527 --> 00:14:06.448
you want to enable. So so I didn't have like any sort of design other than like I'm going to work

00:14:06.448 --> 00:14:12.288
on things that I feel will be important and useful and interesting. And when I was a product person,

00:14:13.247 --> 00:14:19.407
I was exclusively a product person on developer tools or models. So like highly technical,

00:14:19.407 --> 00:14:25.488
like lower level sort of sort of thing. So I was still writing code every day.

00:14:25.488 --> 00:14:26.687
Yeah. Yeah.

00:14:26.687 --> 00:14:31.407
It does really feel like like Cloud Code and similar tools like such a win for people who

00:14:31.407 --> 00:14:33.807
have just got like weird interests in lots of places.

00:14:33.807 --> 00:14:38.927
Exactly. Like it's and and like suddenly all of these things that were like 70 percent

00:14:38.927 --> 00:14:43.328
finished on your GitHub, like you can like actually get out into the world. It's there's

00:14:43.328 --> 00:14:47.888
never been a better time to be a curious human who wants to like create things.

00:14:47.888 --> 00:14:52.527
Yeah. Yeah. Like I made an iPhone app like it's just a little timer for talks, but just like

00:14:52.527 --> 00:14:57.328
something that would be my head for years. And like that's like a weekend project now. It's like

00:14:57.328 --> 00:14:58.208
it's really cool.

00:14:58.208 --> 00:15:05.008
Exactly. I don't have it in my backpack right now, but there's one of my side projects is

00:15:05.888 --> 00:15:12.687
there's something called a cheap yellow display. It's called a CYD ESP32. And it's like this

00:15:12.687 --> 00:15:20.608
little tiny board with just a visualization screen on top. And to update it, you have to

00:15:20.608 --> 00:15:26.048
like rewrite the firmware. So it's not as flexible as something like a Raspberry Pi with the screen.

00:15:27.647 --> 00:15:33.087
But I would have never been able to do anything with it. And now I'm using those to power

00:15:34.048 --> 00:15:39.407
these silent film birdhouses. So it's like you have a birdhouse, you put the little screen on

00:15:39.407 --> 00:15:42.687
the inside, people look through the little hole and you can watch the silent film.

00:15:42.687 --> 00:15:43.247
Oh, my gosh.

00:15:43.247 --> 00:15:43.568
Yeah.

00:15:43.568 --> 00:15:45.087
Wait, that's incredible.

00:15:45.087 --> 00:15:49.087
It's I'm putting them. So I'm putting them around San Francisco as art installations.

00:15:49.087 --> 00:15:49.568
Yeah.

00:15:49.568 --> 00:15:51.967
Like next to the tiny like borrowing libraries.

00:15:51.967 --> 00:15:52.927
Yeah. Oh, my gosh.

00:15:52.927 --> 00:15:58.048
But you can you can have like site specific films for each location.

00:15:58.048 --> 00:16:01.328
And then like there's just ever like a little battery and then that lasts for ages.

00:16:01.328 --> 00:16:07.407
